response_a:
Begin by distributing in the innermost parentheses: \begin{align*}
&\ \ \ \ x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2) \\&= x(x+x^2+2x) - 3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*} Now, distribute again: \begin{align*}
x^2+x^3+2x^2-3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*} Finally, combine like terms to get \begin{align*}
\boxed{x^3+3x-6}
\end{align*}

response_b:
I need to apply the distributive property of multiplication over addition to both terms in the expression.
For the first term, I can multiply x by each term inside the parentheses, and then apply the distributive property again to the x(1+x) term:

\begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right) &= x\left(x+x^2+2x\right) \\
&= x^2+x^3+2x^2
\end{align*}
For the second term, I can multiply -3 by each term inside the parentheses:

\begin{align*}
-3(x^2-x+2) &= -3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*}
Now I can combine the two terms by subtracting the second from the first, and then collect like terms:

\begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2) &= x^2+x^3+2x^2 - (-3x^2+3x-6) \\
&= x^2+x^3+2x^2 + 3x^2-3x+6 \\
&= x^3+6x^2-3x+6
\end{align*}

# Answer

